nfounded by narrow, technocratic understandings of evidence, toxicity, and responsibility. Building on collaborators’ work to contest state and oil company insistence that harm is controlled and principally chemical in nature, Fiske shows that it is necessary to refigure harm as relational in order to reckon with unremediated contamination of the past while pushing for broad forms of accountability in the present. She theorizes that harm is both a relationship and an animating feature of relationships in this place, a contingent understanding that is needed to contemplate what comes next when living in a toxic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEnvironmental justicezAmazon River Region2DLC. 0aLiability for oil pollution damagesxSocial aspectszAmazon River Region2DLC. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexEnvironmental aspectszAmazon River Region2DLC. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexEnvironmental aspectszAmazon River Region. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexSocial aspectszAmazon River Region2DLC. 0aPetroleum law and legislationxSocial aspectszAmazon River Region2DLC. 0aSocial responsibility of businesszAmazon River Region2DLC. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apollution, toxicity, Ecuador, Lago Agrio, oil extraction, oil contamination, toxic tours, legality, anthropology of oil, ethnography, extraction, extraction economy, mestizo, Texaco, Chevron, harm, environmental justice, Amazonian ethnography, Ecuadorian Amazon, environmental anthropology, fieldwork in Latin America, Indigenous Latin America, people of Latin America, Relationality/Relations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G